purpose: "Lightweight documentation standard that captures architectural context AI agents and new developers cannot infer from source code alone"

tensions:
  - "All sections are optional and non-binding — adding mandatory fields or runtime validation would contradict the core philosophy; ContextDoc is documentation, not configuration"
  - "ctx-run must remain provider-agnostic — no hardcoded Anthropic-only logic; LiteLLM handles routing via model string convention (ollama/x, gpt-x, claude-x)"
  - "project.ctx and file-level .ctx serve different scopes — project.ctx captures cross-cutting constraints; file .ctx captures file-specific context; they must not duplicate each other"
  - "Operational instructions (CLAUDE.md, .cursorrules) are separate from context (.ctx) — directives tell agents how to behave; context tells them what the system is; both are needed, neither replaces the other"
  - "A .ctx file should never exceed ~60 lines — the schema enforces no limit but the principle does; if a file needs more, the documentation is probably over-specified"

workflows:
  adoption: "add project.ctx at root → identify highest-risk file → add file.ctx with tensions → add conceptualTests → install git hook → optionally run ctx-run"
  agent_reads: "read project.ctx (cross-cutting constraints) → read file.ctx for target file → respect tensions → use conceptualTests as the spec"

conceptualTests:
  - name: "Minimal valid .ctx"
    steps:
      - action: "create a .ctx file with only a purpose line"
        expect: "valid ContextDoc — schema accepts it, no sections are required"
  - name: "project.ctx scope separation"
    steps:
      - action: "read project.ctx and any file.ctx in the same repo"
        expect: "no duplication — project.ctx has cross-cutting tensions, file.ctx has file-specific ones"
  - name: "ctx-run on project.ctx"
    steps:
      - action: "run ctx-run against project.ctx"
        expect: "conceptualTests are evaluated like any other .ctx file — no special handling needed"
